Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the noodles.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{125%grams} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, boil a half-full #kettle{} for the sauce.

Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed), then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Slice widthways into pieces about 1/2 cm thick.

Drain the @king prawns{300%grams}. 

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat.

Once hot, add the prawns, carrot and @sliced mushrooms{120%grams}. Fry, stirring occasionally, for ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a #measuring jug{}, mix together the @peanut butter{30%grams} and @boiled water{125%milliliters} for the sauce (see pantry for amount) until smooth. Once smooth, stir in the @ketjap manis{25%grams}, @sweet chilli sauce{48%grams} and @soy sauce{25%milliliters} and mix until well combined.

Add the garlic to the frying pan and fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the sauce and bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut the @lime{1} into wedges.

Stir the cooked noodles into the frying pan until coated in the sauce. Add a squeeze of lime juice and stir to combine.

Taste and add more @salt{}, @pepper{} or lime juice if needed.

Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Share the sweet chilli and peanut prawn noodles between your #serving bowls{}.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!